@node film
   ____
  (_  _)             Film at Eleven: Brave New World
   / /                        by @{"Jim Meyer" link jimm}
 _/ /  
(____) t's small, 4 inches wide by 6 inches high, and can fit comfortably
       in most shirt pockets.  It accepts a wide variety of input, and its
ultra high-resolution, high-contrast surface (tens of thousands of dots per
inch) allow a truly jaggie-free display that is visible even in the poorest
lighting conditions.  Furthermore, it's fully capable of high-quality
graphics (with no limit on the number of colors it can display), and even
has the ability to animate at speeds of 30 frames per second or more. (Its
capacity is limited, however.)

This device is truly unbreakable; it has been dropped from airplanes
without sustaining any damage.  And its memory is non-volatile; enter data,
and it will remain until you remove it.  This amazing device features a
built-in appointment scheduler, memo recorder, address and phone databank,
and it fits in well with current fax technology.  It accepts input from a
wide variety of devices, including pen, pencil, crayon, and even magic
marker.  It even comes with several built-in games!  And best of all is the
price: 39 cents.

Would you buy one of these?  It's a memo pad, of course, that familiar
60-page bundle of paper held together by a metal coil.  In fact, you
probably have several.  Now, would you buy its space-age replacement?  It
goes by the acronym of Personal Digital Assistant, or PDA.  It runs on
batteries, is somewhat larger, and costs 1,794 times as much.

The most famous PDA is the @{"Newton" system "$viewer newton"}, from Apple.  At last count, 50,000 of
these techno-whiz machines have been shipped.  While Newton itself is 7.5
inches high by 3.5 inches wide, the screen itself is only around 4 inches
high and 2.4 inches wide.  And the usable area is somewhat smaller than
that, once you subtract the "button" area on the bottom.  The Newton is, of
course, quite breakable, eats batteries for lunch (expect to get from 5 to
32 hours of use per set), has a fairly low-contrast LCD panel, and its
handwriting recognition - supposedly the best of the bunch - is spotty.

But the Newton does have a serial port, can communicate with other Newtons
at close range, and can save you virtually seconds by recognizing key words
(like "fax home") and launching associated macros.  And that's fortunate,
since the tiny working area doesn't leave you much room for sentences.

So what does this have to do with the Amiga?  Nothing and everything.
Newton sales have nothing to do with Amiga sales, of course, and Commodore
doesn't make a PDA.  Yet.  But when you look at the larger picture, it's
interesting to note that Apple is expending considerable resources chasing
this vision of the future.  And they're not alone; just about everybody is
chasing the "pen-based" computer market.  Even our old friend GEOS (for
those of you who hail back to the C64) is in the PDA arena, in the
offerings from Tandy and Casio.

And back in the world of personal computers, Apple once again cut prices on
all its Macintosh products.  You can now get the "entry level" Quadra 605 -
with a 68LC040 processor - for $969.  The keyboard is, of course, extra, as
is a monitor.  If you want to move up the line, to a Quadra 610 with 8 megs
of memory and a 160 Mb hard drive, it'll set you back $1400. Plus that
keyboard and monitor.  (Forgive me if I omit discussion of the
just-released Macintosh TV, by the way.)

Is there any reason for anyone to buy an Amiga 4000?  I wonder.  While
Commodore claims that they can't make them fast enough to satisfy demand,
thus justifying the relatively high price, there is ample evidence that
demand isn't all that high, and production is frighteningly low.  The Amiga
1200, despite being underpowered, remains a fairly good deal, but Commodore
can't afford to make enough of them, either.

In the midst of all this, Apple posted their quarterly results: 2 million
dollars profit, down 97% from last year.  That happens to be about the same
amount of money that Commodore (at least the US operation) made in its most
recent quarter, according to my sources.  And Commodore's sales were
one-eighth that of Apple, at best.

So maybe there's really not much money to be had in this business of
chasing the future.  Yet.  But that doesn't seem to be stopping anyone from
trying.  Over in the PC world, everyone is scrambling to bring their
ancient architectures (16-bit busses, 16-bit operating systems with no
built-in GUI support, segmented memory models) into the present by touting
"multimedia" capabilities.

But just what does "multimedia" mean?  Well, according to PC Magazine, it
means a PC with an added sound card and a CD-ROM drive.  Read for yourself:
"...outfitting a PC for multimedia should be no more difficult than finding
a good all-around PC and installing a CD-ROM drive, a sound board,
speakers, and specialized software." (PC Magazine, Volume 12, Number 18.)

Once again, definitions like this are probably news to Amiga owners, who
thought "multimedia" meant nothing more than combining graphics, text, and
sound.  And what kind of advanced machine is required to pull off this
modern-day miracle?  Well, interestingly enough, an Amiga 500, 600, 1000,
1200, 2000, 3000, or 4000 will suffice.  Want proof?  Ask anyone who ever
bought an issue of AMnews, the late, lamented, multimedia magazine.  It ran
in as little as 1 meg of memory, on processors as slow as the 68000.  Of
course, AMnews folded for good in 1989.

Now, I don't want to cry wolf, but I have to wonder where we're supposed to
be headed with this new "digital revolution."  Want a good indication?
 Flip to the back of Compute, of Multimedia, or even PC Magazine.  You'll
see the best that multimedia has to offer: ErotiCafe, available on Mac or
PC CD-ROM; Wicked, starring Teri Weigel, available on Photo-CD; BodyCello,
featuring "adults only software."  If you want to see first-hand, go to a
Mac Expo or Comdex.

So there you have it.  Technology at your fingertips.  You can order a
fax with the stroke of a pen, or you can ogle a fox with the click of a
mouse.  To do the former, all you have to do is plunk down 700 dollars or
so for a PDA.  To do the latter, all you need is $1800 to $2800 and the
latest powerhouse PC or top-of-the-line Mac.  And "virtual reality" is
right around the corner.  Anyone care to hazard a guess as to where that
will take us?

I make no promises, but I'm willing to bet that there are surprises in
store.  Intel's reign may be about to end; Robert Dewar and Matthew Smosna,
writing in Open Systems Today, speak of the "inherently incoherent"
instruction set of the x86 chips and their "junky design features."  They
predict that the PowerPC chip - which will support a variety of operating
systems - will be the clear winner.  Just in time for Cybersex.


