@node guns
    __  __
   / / / /                  PROFILE: YOUNG GUNS
  / / / /                      by @{"Paul Rigby" link paulr}
 / (_/ / 
(_____/ nhappy with the lack of support and advice for potential Amiga
graphics users, three young video makers have set out to change the
situation by making a tutorial video with a difference. Amiga Mart talked
to them. They are: Edward Procktor, 20; David Charles, 21 and Catherine
Clarke, 17.

 WHAT IS THE VIDEO ABOUT?

Learning anything new is difficult and computers particularly so. If you
are just getting started in Amiga graphics there are very few places you
can go for help. If you are buying an Amiga for the first time then you
need good advice to make sure you get what you need and not what the
salesman wants to sell you. I can remember buying my first Amiga. It was an
A500 and I was very pleased I had been talked into buying one with a Fat
Agnus, I had no idea what a Fat Agnus was but it sounded cool. What we aim
to do is give the viewer a good understanding of the basic concepts of
computing and graphics so they can make informed decisions about what they
actually need to create the graphics they want. We want to get them past
all the jargon and on their way to producing images on the Amiga.

 WHO IS IT FOR?

Anyone who needs to understand Amiga graphics, particularly those who
are not coming from computing backgrounds. This is the ideal guide for
artists or graphic designers who want to use computer graphics in their
projects. Another example are camcorder users who want to add captions and
titles into their videos. The chances are they know the Amiga is their best
choice and they have been told they need something called a `genlock' but
where do they go for more information. Literally anybody at any level of
experience or any level of equipment should find this useful.

 WHY USE A VIDEO?

Tutorial videos are a great way of learning because you can actually
demonstrate and show what you are talking about. What better way to learn
about graphics than by watching them. With a book or a magazine article it
is hard to describe what is happening visually and you can only have so
many photographs. With video you have full color TV sized photographs at 25
per second. The science programme Tomorrow's World is a great example of
how complex concepts can be explained to those without specialist knowledge.

 DO YOU HAVE A PARTICULARLY ORIGINAL STYLE THEN?

We think so, yes. Most computer videos are boring. They are men in suits
talking to the camera for 90 minutes or a voice-over that is either five
minutes ahead or five minutes behind the action they are explaining. We
believe that learning should be fun. The style does not really matter, as
long as the viewer learns what they need know and remembers it.

SO WHERE IS THE MONEY GOING?

Once all of the production costs have been repaid then all of the profits
are going to a charity called the PEPER HAROW ORGANISATION that helps
abused children cope with their experiences. It took me a while to convince
Dave that we had to give all of the money away.

 HOW DID YOU CHOOSE THE CHARITY?

Well I always knew the charity we chose should be one that worked in that
area and so Dave and I sat down with a long list of charities and picked
out Peper Harow. We considered all of the charities that work in that area
and we liked the kind of work they were doing. The fact they were not a
well known concern was also very important. The larger charities can afford
to advertise and have a higher profile but the smaller ones need  to spend
all their money on their work and can only get publicity when things like
this happen.

 HOW DID YOU ALL GET TOGETHER?

Well Dave and I spent three years at college together and we both thought
the media courses we were doing had too much theory so we started working
on practical projects outside college. We work well together because I come
up with all the wacky ideas and Dave trims them down to size. He keeps
things realistic, makes sure what I want to do is actually possible. Most
of the time I have more ideas than I know what to do with. You should
always  have someone to test your ideas on. Dave is also less interested in
the graphics side of the Amiga and so he makes sure I do not lapse into
technical jargon.

Catherine had worked on some of my more recent projects and so Dave
suggested she would ideal to help us out. She has always been interested in
video and she really is a good worker - she is smarter than us too.

 SO HOW DID THE IDEA COME ABOUT?

Well I had the idea in June 1993. It came right in the middle of some
rather important exams so I had to try and forget about it for two months
and get on with revision. After my exams I told Dave about it and he said
it sounded like a great idea. It was originally a video exclusively about
24-bit graphics but we decided that the audience for such a video would be
so small it would not raise much money for the charity so we  expanded it
to include all types of graphics. After that it  became more and more
beginner orientated.

So we worked on developing the video off and on over the last year doing
other things at the same time. It was in May when things really got going
we and discovered we needed some help so we made a few calls to people who
had worked on our projects before to see if anyone was free to give a hand
and Catherine was. We were both impressed by her previous work and were
glad to have her aboard. Even though she has not been with us since the
beginning she slotted right in and we all share the creative and practical
tasks. Now I am working on it full time and Dave and Catherine help out
when they can.

 IS THERE ANYONE ELSE HELPING YOU?

We have had a great response from those we have approached. A lot of
organizations have been helpful and we have of specialists who work in
computing and video who give up their time to hear our ideas and help us
out when we need it. We have a great accountant who helps us with business
advice as well. She normally charges 10 per hour but she gives us her time
for free.

 WHAT HAS BEEN THE HARDEST ASPECT OF MAKING THE VIDEO?

The script - definitely. The hardest thing was deciding the order in which
you explain things. A lot of our audience will have never owned an Amiga
before and so we need to tell them about RAM and custom chips and
accelerators as well as paint  packages and image processors. After using
an Amiga for three years words like overscan, 24-bit and anti-aliasing
become second nature. It is hard going back to explaining the basics.

The fact that the products change and are continually developing is
annoying as well. When all the new Amigas kept popping up it was a struggle
to keep up. We do not focus on specific products however so in theory this
video will not date. A paint package is a paint package whether it works in
32 colors or 32-bits.

WHAT STAGE ARE YOU AT THE MOMENT?

We have finally finished the script and are about to start filming so it is
not too late for people to contact us. We are still willing to consider
featuring peoples products or peoples work.

 WHEN WE WILL SEE THE VIDEO?

Well we hope to have it ready by the end of October and so it should be
available by Christmas. We do not have a distributor although we open to
offers so we will probably distribute it ourselves via mail order.

 SO WHAT IS NEXT FOR YOU?

I have been thinking about re-editing the video to sell abroad in America,
Europe and Australia. I already have my next two projects planned out and I
cannot wait to get started on them. For the next Amiga project I would like
to get involved in the area of Amiga produced drama programmes. Something
along the lines of Babylon 5 or Seaquest DSV. There is no reason why anyone
cannot just go out and do it. As long as you have confidence and are
prepared to put the effort required into it then there is  no reason why
anyone cannot make it succeed. I think I might have a rest first. I have
been dying to read a good novel for ages.  My head has been full of
magazine articles, textbooks and manuals, I simply have not had room for
anything else.

Contact: Edward Procktor/David Charles,
         PO Box 3503,
         London, SW19 2ER.

(Copyright © 1993, Amiga Mart Magazine.  Reprinted with permission)


