@node proper

 ______
(__  __)                     Proper Grammar II
  / /                        by @{"Norman Harris" link normanh}
 / /  
(_/ here are no excuses for any grammatical errors in this review. At least
if there are it's not my fault, as Proper Grammar II from SoftWood has
thoroughly checked, and successfully passed this review.

Due to the size of its dictionary, Proper Grammar II requires installation
onto a hard drive - it cannot run from floppy disks.

This dictionary contains linguistic information on over 135,000 words. It
is refreshing to see that it uses British spelling, so you won't get caught
out with the American dictionaries used in some Word Processors. Along with
spelling mistakes, Proper Grammar can check for punctuation, style and
grammar.

The screen display is very similar to SoftWood's word processor, Final Copy
II, but with the screen split into three parts. Into the lower section you
load your text for Proper Grammar to check.

The program accepts files saved from most popular word processors -
ProWrite, Pen Pal, Scribble, Excellence, TransWrite, Final Copy, KindWords,
TextCraft, QuickWrite, as well as ASCII text. If for any reason Proper
Grammar finds any formatting commands that it cannot process, it displays a
warning message and then inserts that information at the end of your
document. While saving from Proper Grammar is normally done in the same
format as was loaded, you can save in any other format. In this way you can
use Proper Grammar to convert documents from one word processor's format to
another.

Once loaded, Proper Grammar starts checking your document a sentence at a
time. First it checks the spelling, not only for incorrectly spelt words,
but also for similarly sounding words. For instance, in the first paragraph
of this review it told me that the word "passed" sounded like "past", give
me the meaning of both words and asked me to check which was correct. If
for some reason I had indicated that "past" was correct, the program could
not detect that the context was wrong. Right away it shows a weakness in
this type of program, as it can only assist in correcting a document. It
cannot understand the meaning of the text to know what is right or wrong.

If you come across a correctly spelt word that Proper Grammar does not
recognize, adding it to the user dictionary will prevent it being flagged
as an error in the future. Proper Grammar can act as a sort of mini
word-processor allowing basic cut and paste facilities for correcting
errors. Unfortunately you cannot print from the program and there are no
formatting commands, so it will not entirely replace a word-processor.

Proper Grammar checks for a whole host of punctuation errors. The sort of
errors the program recognizes includes - the first word of a sentence must
always be capitalized, the correct way to use numbers, using symbols as
abbreviations, parenthesis and quotation marks, missing spaces, and many
others. While Proper Grammar normally carried out a thorough job of
spotting punctuation errors, it always seemed to fall down in identifying
incorrectly capitalized words.

Then it starts on the grammar of the document. Many of the errors that
Proper Grammar flags may be down to your specific style of writing. You can
tailor the program to recognize your writing style by letting you switch
various grammatical rules off to prevent them being flagged as errors. The
danger in doing this is that you will also ignore unintentional errors. In
addition, to switch the error flags off requires a good grammatical
knowledge.

If you don't understand the meaning of terms such as noun adjuncts or
subordinating conjunctions, then Proper Grammar will usually offer an
explanation when flagging an error. What it cannot do is correctly rephrase
the sentence for you. The manual itself is very helpful at explaining
unfamiliar jargon and offers a good glossary of grammatical terms.

Statistical reports are also available concerning the length of the
document, in words and sentences. This information is broken-down further
into word length, syllables per word, words per sentence, etc. Proper
Grammar uses this information to provide such things as a Flesch Reading
Ease Score, a Flesch-Kincaid Grade Level and a Gunning's Fog Index.
Although I had seen references to these before, I must admit I didn't have
a clue what they meant. According to these statistics this review rates a
"Fairly difficult" on the Flesch Reading Ease Score, and Proper Grammar
informs me that only around 54% of American adults would understand it. The
Gunning's Fog Index of 12.71 tells me that it's more difficult to
understand than most news magazines which rate about a 10.

I can't help feeling that the people who will understand most about what
the program is trying to do will be those that need it least. If you
already understand the grammatical terms used do you really need this
program? In fact, would you appreciate Proper Grammar questioning your use
of the English language? On the other hand Proper Grammar can help those
that want to learn. Running a few documents through Proper Grammar can tell
you a lot about your writing style and may encourage you to change. Keep
the manual close by in case you need clarification of those grammatical
terms and, if it doesn't do anything else, Proper Grammar should find
typing errors that a spell checker normally misses.

Proper Grammar II
$99.95
SoftWood, Inc.
P.O. Box 50178
Phoenix, AZ 85076
(800) 247-8330

(Copyright © 1993, Amiga Mart Magazine.  Reprinted with permission.)


@{" Previous Article " link vlab} @{" Table of Contents " link Main} @{" Next Article " link kidpix}

@endnode

@node kidpix

 ______
(__  __)           KIDPIX - Silly Fun for Any Generation
  / /                        by @{"Sylvia Lutnes" link sylvial}
 / /  
(_/ his painting program for kids and those of us who refuse to grow up is
giggly fun. If you're an 'adult', be sure you're alone when you use it,
otherwise it could be embarrassing. At the least, turn up your stereo so
the sound effects on every mouseclick will drown out your chuckles.

KidPix, by Broderbund, is an import and as such only works in PAL mode.
Know this right off. If PAL is a problem for you, then you'll have to pass
on this one. I use KidPix on my 4000/040 and all that is necessary is
holding down both mouse buttons at bootup and selecting PAL. Once Workbench
is up, I go to Prefs and select a PAL screen. Even if the system is in PAL
mode, the screen must be also. (Being in NTSC mode and using a PAL
resolution Workbench is not enough.) KidPix is HD installable and
multitasks...it even honors mode promotion and coexists peacefully with my
commodities.

There is a 'Small Kids Mode' you can select from the menu which will leave
only the option 'Show Menu Bar' available. How much protection this affords
you is up to you. Depending on the age of your kids, you may want to boot
directly from floppy instead of the harddrive.

Since this is a kid's program, I only read the addenda that tells the
differences between the Amiga and other versions (more on that later),
and tucked the manual away. I figure a kid isn't going to read the manual
anyway and the parent will do the installing. So I did the best thing
possible, I explored this program figuring out how to use it. Most fun
I've had in a long time.

When the program opens, it looks like any normal paint program. Down the
left side of the @{"screen" system "$viewer kp.000"} is a panel of colorful icons that represent your
tools. Along the bottom is a panel of options that work with the selected
tool plus the palette colors. The fun begins when you click on a tool.

Let's choose the pencil at the top. Click on a color, click on a fill
pattern and pen size, now draw. Click the question mark. Now your pen will
change colors as it draws. Almost every set of options has a '?' that will
give you something special. With the straight-line tool, the '?' will draw
rays that change the color underneath...giving you a neat moire effect. But
if you're stamping individual letters on the screen the '?' draws a
question mark and a voice says 'HUH?'.

Had enough? Then let's kill this picture right now. Choose the eraser and
click on the firecracker option. Click in the middle of the screen and
KABOOOOOOM. Or watch it fade away, slide away, count down to oblivion, or
many other options. Try the '?' with the eraser tool for a very nice
surprise.

Draw some boxes on your new empty screen. Fill them with colors or
patterns. Choose the brush tool and have some more fun. Want dripping paint
with sound effects? Or fractal trees that are different everywhere you
click? Or paint splotches, or random dice, or an entire deck of cards? Or,
whew. Let's nuke it and start again.

Doodle some more. Then choose the hand mixer icon. Let's checkerboard it.
Or outline everything. Or magnify part of it. Or tile it. Or, oh my. I'm
going to be at this all night. But first I want to turn night into day and
have the snowflakes all over the place. And I still want to make my own
connect-the-numbered-dots picture.

And I haven't even used the stamps yet. Dozens of built in brushes of
everything from flowers to aliens, trains to eyeglasses, flowers, furniture
and animals. If we don't like where we put the house, we can select the
truck tool and move it (and listen to the engine and hear the brakes squeal
as it comes to a stop). We can even edit the brushes.

There are, however, a few things missing from the Amiga version. There's no
music. (The sound effects are a gas, though.) The brushes can only be
enlarged, they can't be rotated and that can be a little frustrating, and
the qualifier keys available on some of the options don't work (what's a
qualifier key, mommy?).

Pictures can be saved for grandma. They can also be printed. I couldn't
test the printing because my new printer driver crashes when I print
graphics from any program. The pictures are not in IFF format, however, so
if daddy wants to brushmap his child's masterpiece into Imagine, he'll have
to screen grab (talk about qualifier keys). This also means we can't load
in other pictures to doodle over. What I would like to see, however, is for
one of the regular Amiga paint programs, read Brilliance, to add some of
the neat drawing tools to their repertoire. I guess asking for the sound
effects also would be expecting too much. (I didn't say that.)

I, kid that I am, enjoy this program tremendously. I've even screen grabbed
an entire series of fractal trees which now grace a VistaPro scene. I can't
imagine (other) kids not having fun with KIDPIX.

   KIDPIX

   from Broderbund
   distributed by ELECTRONIC ARTS
   Langley Business Centre
   11-49 Station Road, Langley
   Berks, England SL3 8YN

   Tel (0753) 549442

   Available through importers and dealers
   (approximately $30-35)


