@node brill

    _____
   / _   )           Brilliance: The Lost Tutorials
  / / ) /                     by @{"Jim Meyer" link jimm}
 / (_/ / 
(_____/ ptimism, like hope, springs eternal.  And so it was that earlier
this year, while Digital Creations was scrambling to bring Brilliance to
market, Bob Eller and I delivered the "final" version of the Brilliance
manual, with the understanding that Brilliance would be released within
weeks.

Three months later, it finally happened.  And not only were there changes
to the software, but the manual had changed, as well.  Gone was the
Tweening tutorial I had slaved over - "On Alien Pond" - and in its place
was a tutorial featuring the artwork of Jim Sachs.  Now, one look at the
artwork that accompanies this tutorial will convince you that I pose no
threat to Jim Sachs.  However, the revised tutorials glossed over many of
the more important features of Brilliance animation.  My intent, with this
article, is to fill in some of the voids.

Perspective

Perspective can be a tough concept to grasp.  First of all, the computer is
a 2-dimensional medium.  The image area of a monitor has height and width,
but it has no depth.  The software of a paint program is able to compensate
for this by operating in 3-dimensional space, but it remains for the
programmer to provide the means for the user to operate within this space.

Width and height are easy to convey.  Assuming you're in an upright
position, width is right and left, and height is up and down.  But what
about depth?  Depth can be described as "to and fro," or "close and far."
 In the mathematical world of the computer, location is determined with
@{"three axes:" system $viewer Axes-3"} x, y, and z.  The x axis is horizontal, and the y axis is
vertical.  The z axis, however, is theoretical, at least in 2-D terms. Try
this: Imagine a line running from the tip of your nose to the center of the
monitor.  That's the z axis!

Because of the peculiarities of vision, objects appear to become smaller as
they move further away.  And parallel lines will tend to converge as they
run off into the distance.  Anyone who has looked down a long stretch of
railroad tracks or a highway knows this phenomenon.  In @{"perspective" system "$viewer Perspect"}
drawing, the point at which parallel lines meet is called the Origin, or
the Vanishing Point. Perspective drawing programs utilize a set of
imaginary lines, running along the Z axis, that converge at the origin. As
an object travels along those lines, it will be scaled accordingly  to
convey the illusion of distance.

But I digress; we were speaking of axes.  There are two different
components of perspective, where the axes are concerned: movement along an
axis, and rotation about an axis.  We've already alluded to movement; when
you move an object along the x axis, you move it left and right. When you
move an object along the y axis, you move it up and down.  But when you
move an object along the z axis, you move it closer to you or further away.

@{"Rotation" system "$viewer Rotate-3"} is similar, but requires a different visualization.  Imagine an
airplane.  The propeller represents rotation around a particular axis. If
you view the airplane from the side, the propeller rotates around the x
axis.  If you stand the airplane on its tail, the propeller rotates around
the y axis.  And if you point the airplane toward you, the propeller
rotates around the z axis.

Ease

Ease makes Perspective look easy.  The technical explanation is this: Ease
lets you vary the speed of an object as it moves.  Assume that there is a
"normal" speed.  If you use 60 frames, and move a brush 300 pixels to the
right, it will move at a rate of 5 pixels per frame.

Ease lets you change that, though.  You can have the brush move more
quickly at first and slow down at the end.  Or you can have it move slowly
at first and speed up.  And then there's XOVER; this little control lets
you split the "range" into a beginning section and an ending section.  For
example, let's say you set XOVER at 25%.  That would mean that the Start
control would govern the first 15 frames, and the End control would govern
the last 45 frames.

But first, we need to talk about the Start and End controls.  Both have a
range that goes from -99 to 99.  (A setting of 0 results in no change in
speed over that range.)  Exactly what those numbers mean, however, tends to
get confusing.  The simplest explanation I've been able to come up with is
this:  The Ease numbers determine what happens at the END of a range, with
positive numbers meaning acceleration, and negative numbers meaning
deceleration.

For example, let's say you've drawn a diagonal line, starting at the top
left-hand side of the screen and ending at the bottom right-hand side.
You've set the starting and ending positions of your brush so that it too
will travel from the top left to the bottom right.

Now, if you set the Xover at 50% and the X ease for Start at 99, the object
will travel along an arc on the underside of the diagonal, meeting the
diagonal at mid-point and then traveling along the diagonal.  In other
words, it started traveling from left to right at a slower rate of speed
than normal, and ended (at the midpoint) at a higher rate. And if you set
the X ease at -99, you'll get an arc above the diagonal.

Using this same @{"example" system "$viewer Ease.pic"}, we can see how Xover lets us get two different
curves. If you set the X ease at 99 for Start and -99 for end, you'll get a
path that arcs below the diagonal for the first half, and above the
diagonal for the second half.

Putting it All Together

Now that you've (hopefully) got the basic concepts and terminology of 3-D
and ease down, it's time to have a little fun.  We'll revisit the
Brilliance tutorial - the one with the fish - but will introduce
perspective and "ease."  We'll assume that you already know the basics of
animation, and we'll dispense with the more rudimentary instructions.

1 - Load the fish picture (tutorial.pic) from the Tutorial drawer in Disk
3. While you're at it, right-click on the Stencil tool to summon the
Stencil menu, and load the "foreground.sten" stencil.  We'll use that, as
well.

2 - Bring up the Animation menu, and use the SET #... button to create 30
frames for this animation.  Since you loaded the image first, it will
appear in all frames.

3 - You'll need one of the fish as a brush.  First, you should set your
background color to blue.  Click on the "pick color" gadget, and then
right-click on the blue water in the fish tank.  Then, click on the Cut
Brush gadget until the lasso appears.  Use the lasso to cut out one of the
fish as a brush.  Since all of the fish are facing the wrong way for our
purposes, you'll need to reverse whichever one you choose.  Just press the
"x" key to flip the fish brush horizontally.

4 - Now, here's the plan:  We'll use the Tween settings to make this fish
swim to the right and to the back, away from us.  And since sea water
tends to be murky, we'll have the fish fade from sight as it swims off
into the distance.  Use these settings for Start:

START          X       Y       Z      END            X       Y       Z
Position      -128    -11      0      Position       12      72      143
Rotation       0       0       0      Rotation       0      -32      0
Opacity        100                     Opacity       100

Set the Count to 20; we're going to do this animation in 2 steps.  And
since we want to leave the display at the next empty frame, click once
on the Go Back gadget so that it is no longer selected.

A quick look at those numbers will show that the fish started out to the
left of center (a negative x number) and moved to the right.  It also
started a little above center (negative y number) and moved down.  The z
number indicates that it started out "on the screen," so to speak, and
moved further away.  The rotation - in the z plane - spins the fish
slightly counter-clockwise, when viewed from above.

So far, we've set up some movement and rotation.  But the fish moves in a
straight line at a constant speed.  This results in an unnatural aspect to
the movement of the fish, something we can remedy with the Ease controls.

5 - Click on the y gadget in the Ease area.  We'll set the y ease
controls so that the downward movement of the fish starts off
quickly, slows to normal speed by mid-point, and then slows down and
speeds up again.  Use these settings:

Y Ease: Start = -99  End = 99  Xover = 50%

6 - Click on Preview to make sure that everything works right.  If it does,
click on Draw.

7 - We still have 10 frames left in which to cause our fish to swim off
into the murkiness of the depths.  First, make sure that you're on frame
20.  Then, click on the E->S button to transfer all the ending positions
into the starting fields.  That lets us pick up where we left off.

8 - First, set the Count to 10.  Now, we'll have the fish do a leisurely
turn as it bobs off and disappears into the distance.  Use the following
settings:

START          X       Y       Z      END            X       Y       Z

Position       12      72      143    Position       102     40      1000
Rotation       0      -32      0      Rotation       0      -80      0
Opacity        100                     Opacity       0

Again, click on Preview to make sure that everything is OK.  Then, click
on Draw.  Once you've finished, sit back and enjoy your @{"animation!" link fish}

