@node class

     _____
    / ____)  The Uploads of September - In a Class by Themselves!
   / /                         by @{"Nick Cook" link nickc}
  / /
 / (____ lass! Class! Now attention please! I need to check the attendance.
(______/ Everybody's here...wait, where's Jim D.? What? Oh, he's gone? That's
right, I keep forgeting three years _is_ a long time to be in this class. Now
class, it's time for show and tell. Who wishes to be first? Yes, Deb."

"Miss C, I want to share WBTRIS (#20815 WBTRIS1.LHA 53504 bytes). Its a
little Tetris clone by Ralf Pieper and Dirk Böhmer. I think they're
Germans. You play the game on any public screen, like Workbench, but
it's got to be 2.0 and above. The graphics are clean with a 3D look to
the tiles. It is fun. The end."

"Thank you, Deb. Next? Yes, Peggy."

"I want to share Yactris--"

"Bless you."

"No! Yactris is 'Yet Another Clone TRIS' (#20898 YACTRIS-V0.1.LHA
101248 bytes) by Jonathan Springer. It multi-tasks and will open on any
public screen. This one has music, too! But you need 2.0. It is fun.
The end."

"Thank you. All right, Jim M., you've waved your hand a while. What do
you want to share?"

"Well, ma'am, I want to share Jure Vrhovnik's Sizetris (#20929
SIZETRIS10.LHA 25600 bytes), another multitasking, system friendly,
game of Tetris--"

"Good grief! Not another Tetris game!"

"Miss C, you shouldn't make negative comments concerning my selection.
You could irreparably damage my self-esteem, ensuring my plummet down
the social spiral, ending up in prison with convicted felons making
furniture."

"Uh, no, I wouldn't want to cause that. Proceed."

"Sizetris can be played from Workbench or CLI. The game simply opens a
small window, which can be moved or sized as you like. It is fun. The
end."

"Thank you, Jim. Bob! Bob E! I've already told you three times: you may
NOT play with your Uzi in class. Please put it back in your backpack
until recess. Thank you. Next? Yes, Janice."

"I want to share AHextris (#20819 AHEXTRIS.LHA 34176 bytes) by Ives
Aerts. This version of Tetris--"

"sigh."

"Are you getting one of your headaches again, Miss C.? Well, AHextris uses
hexagon pieces instead of square ones. It makes the game as fresh and as
addictive as the original. 2.0 required. It is the funnest. The end."

"Thank you. I hope _that_ is the last Tetris. Who's next?"

"Me, Miss C. I have Quip (#20901 QUIP7E.LHA 327936 bytes) by Joseph
Edwards Van Riper III. It is a program that tosses various quips and
wise sayings on the screen. For example, Quip #74 'It is bad luck to be
superstitious'. Or #698: 'If you would keep a secret from an enemy,
tell it not to a friend'. Quip runs from CLI or Workbench, and needs
the Req.library, but that is included. Quip lets you adjust its display
through various tool types, and even includes its own language, so you
can write scripts. Joseph Edwards Van Riper III says that this program
is useful to those running a Citadel BBS. Quip is silly. It is fun.
The end."

"Thank you. A quip a day keeps the philosophers away! He,he,he. Next?
Yes, Thomas."

"My program is called WhatIs (#20941 FILEID20.LHA 40576 bytes). WhatIs
is a little library and small program for identifying over 500
different file types. 'Cept it calls ASCII files 'unknown data type.'
Hmmm. Install the library in your libs: directory, put WhatIs in your C
directory, and use the CLI. It is handy. The end."

"Thank you, Thomas. Next? Yes, Denny."

"Buy my homework."

"Ah, thank you, Denny."

"It's only $19.95."

"_Thank you_, Denny, but that does not compute. Yes, Andy?"

"I want to share Croak (#20995 CROAK.LZH 88064 bytes). This is a very
playable version of the old arcade game, Frogger. See the frog jump.
Jump, frog, jump. Watch out for that truck! See the frog smushed on the
road. See the frog. See the frog jump across the river. Watch out,
frog. See the frog go glub-glub. Graphics are kinda crude and the
sound is minimal. It is fun, anyway. I liked it when the frog goes
splat and leaves a bloodstain on the highway. The end."

"Thank you, Andy. Irving, Irving! Stop loaning money to everybody! What
do you think this is, a multinational corporation? Now, who's next?
Lew?"

"I want to share a program that didn't work. CDTV-Player (#20924
CDTV-PLAYER2_25.LHA 145920 bytes) is a good idea. It is supposed to let
you play audio disks from Workbench, using a nice interface.
Unfortunately, it would not control a ParNETed CDTV when the program
was launched on the A3000 or out of the CDTV unit's RAM. It did not
acknowledge a CD in the drive at all. It was not fun. The end.

"That is a disappointment. Next?"

"I have CxPak (#20893 CKPAK_V1.LHA 27136 bytes), Pierre-Louis
Mangeard's collection of five commodities. They are AutoClick (a window
activator), WClose (click anywhere in a window to close it), WCycle
(click anywhere in a window to cycle screens or windows), WDrag (click
anywhere in a window and drag it), WSize (click anywhere in a window
and size it). Requires 2.0 +. They are small and handy. The end.

"Good jo--Irving, stop it! Stop trying to buy those commodities! Now,
who's next?"

"I want to share a perverter."

"Gasp!"

"Gosh, Miss C., I didn't know your hair could stand on end like that.
Perverter (#20926 PERVERTER1-12.LHA 11904 bytes) is an utility which
converts odd music mods like HanniTracker, ProRunner, LaxityTracker,
and 9 others into NoiseTracker mods. Unfortunately, every mod I loaded
turned out to already be a NoiseTracker mod (according to Perverter),
so I can't test if it works or not. The interface is intuitive, but the
cutsie labels and window titles are almost obnoxious. Docs are on
line. The end."

"I don't know if I want to go on. All right, next."

"Shiver me timbers! I've got an Amiga port of a favorite C64 arcade
game, Popeye (#20993 POPEYE.LHA 470016 bytes). Complete with bloopy
music and blocky graphics! And no docs to figure out how to play it!
But, hey, it's fun, and there's a nifty mini-demo that makes you think
you're watching a cartoon! Popeye requires some disk set up, and is
best run off its own disk. According to the author, there were some
copyright problems with a couple of C commands (but not the
character?). Things must be different in Holland. It was fun. Blow me
down. Toot, toot."

"Thank you for sharing, class. Now, get out our math worksheets. Yes?
Dee? You can't read this number? Watch, I'll trace it for you. See,
Dee, 32. Oh, dear! There goes the Crisis Alarm bell again! All right,
class, who can remember what we have to do? Yes, Mikey."

"Run around screaming and panicing and saying this horse is dead and
race to the nearest clone dealer and buy everything because it is
culturally unacceptable to be different and laughed at by your
neighbors then line up single file and face the school quietly."

"Very good, Mikey. Let's go, class."

