@endnode

@Node ARXTUTORIAL "Viewport       Running with ARexx"
     ____
    / ___)                  Running with ARexx
   / (_                       by @{"Robin Evans" link robinr}
  / ___) 
 / (__ven those who don't wish to write ARexx scripts can benefit from this
(_____) month's ARexx tutorial. A too-frequent problem encountered by folks
trying to run scripts written by others is "Error 15: Function not found."
The error is often easily fixed by adding a something called a function
library to the system.

This tutorial explains the ADDLIB() function that is used to add
libraries, and offers some hints on pitfalls to avoid.

An @{"example program" link ARXTEXINTRO} is included that can be used as a more-informative
alternative to the ADDLIB() function.

ARexx includes over 80 built-in functions. They are a versatile and
powerful collection of program elements, but often not enough for
machine-specific tasks. With a few significant exceptions, the built-in
functions of ARexx are common to all versions of the REXX language. That
commonality limits their ability to perform machine-specific tasks.

The solution lies in external function packages. Dozens of function
libraries have been written for ARexx -- many of them available as
public-domain or shareware files. Among the available libraries are some
that allow an ARexx program to harness the power of the Amiga's graphic
user interface by using windows with buttons, gadgets, and menus. The
file 'rexxarplib.library' is the classic of the GUI function add-ons.
Another is 'rx_intui.library'.

Before any of the functions in an external library can be used, however,
ARexx must be aware of the function library. It has to know where to
look to find the new functions. The built-in function ADDLIB() gives
ARexx a shopping list of libraries.

This is the syntax:

   Bool = ADDLIB(@{"<library name>" link ARXTNAME}, @{"<priority>" link ARXTPRI}, @{"<offset>" link ARXTOFF}, @{"[<version>]" link ARXTVER})

The function returns a Boolean value (either 0 for FALSE, or 1 for
TRUE), but the value isn't very useful. A FALSE return usually means
that the name was already on the library list, but a TRUE return does
not mean that the library is available.

Using ADDLIB() is like jotting an item on a grocery list. If you need a
kumquat for a recipe, it isn't enough just to add the word to your
grocery list. It's a good start, but you still have to go to the store
to buy the thing.

ARexx doesn't "go to the store" -- it doesn't load the library until it
encounters a function call that can't be resolved using its currently
available functions. It doesn't load the library until it has looked on
its shelves and discovered that the item isn't available.

A TRUE return from ADDLIB doesn't even mean that the library exists. The
following will return a "1" even if there is no library with the
specified name:

      say addlib('foo.library',0,-30,0)    >>> 1

The problem with the library name may crop up later in the program and
will be assciated with a function call.

      say foo('Bar')

This instruction will generate an error:

      +++ Error 14 in line <#>: Requested library not found

When the function foo() was used, ARexx searched for the function in
each library on its list. When it came to 'foo.library', the interpreter
noticed that it had not yet been loaded. Only then did ARexx attempt to
load the library, finally discovering that it was not present in the
libs: directory.

Adding a non-existent name to the Library List can cause odd behavior in
other scripts. The name stays on the list even after the program that
put it there exits. ARexx will continue to try to load the library
whenever it runs across an unresolved function call.

That makes it difficult to add new libraries to the List, since they may
have a lower @{"search_priority" link ARXTPRI} than the non-existent library. If a
program generates Error 14 even for functions that you know are present
in one of the added libraries, you should check the List. You can do
that with this shell command: rx "say show('L',, '0a'x)". Check the
names and make sure that a library matching each '.library' name is
present in the libs: directory@{" * " link ARXTHOST}.

To remove a library from the list, use the REMLIB() function:

   say remlib('foo.library')        >>> 1

This function takes a case-sensitive library name as its only argument.
If the name was on the list, it will be removed and the function will
return a TRUE value.

Those who frequently run ARexx programs may find it useful to add some
libraries to the system during the startup sequence. Doing so doesn't
take up much memory because the libraries aren't loaded until they are
needed. It does assure that the library will be searched if one of its
functions is used in a program.

The library can be added to the list and loaded immediately using our
example program. This line added to s:User-Startup will do that:

   rx "call CheckLib('rexxsupport.library')

Since the library may not be needed during the current session, however,
a more memory-efficient alternative is to use ADDLIB() directly:

   rx "call addlib('rexxsupport.library',0,-30,0)

Current versions of the Amiga OS provide a third alternative that is
useful in a startup file. The command utility RXLIB performs the same
task as ADDLIB(), but it is an AmigaDOS command that can be used
directly in a startup file. The syntax is similar to ADDLIB() except
that AmigaDOS-style parsing is used so commas should be omitted along
with the quotation marks around the library name (which is, however,
still case-sensitive):

    rxlib rexxsupport.library 0 -30 0

@{" Previous Article " link class} @{" Table of Contents " link Main} @{" Nancy's 'toon " link toon}

@endnode

@Node ARXTEXINTRO "ViewPort ARexx tutorial -- About the example program"

The example program in the next node, is a different type of function --
an external function. The program code should be saved to your REXX:
directory as "CheckLib.rexx". "CheckLib" can then be called as a
function in any ARexx script. It uses the same syntax as ADDLIB, except
that the priority, offset, and version numbers may be omitted with this
function:

   if CheckLib('rexxsupport.library') then ...

The function returns TRUE if the library was added to the list, but
unlike ADDLIB(), this function will cause the library to be loaded. If
the library could not be loaded, the name will be removed from the
Library List and the function will return FALSE -- a "0".

The function will return FALSE if any library on the list cannot be
loaded, but it is able to remove only the name that was passed to it as
an argument. It's a good idea, then, to use this function for any
doubtful library names.

   Saving the program code
   ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
Users of version 34 of AmigaGuide can save the code by moving to the
following node and choosing "Select all" (Amiga-[) from the "Edit" menu.
Choose "Copy" (Amiga-C) from the same menu to copy the text to the
clipboard, and then load a text editor that supports clipboard
operations. Choose "Insert from clipboard" or "Paste" in the editor and
the program should appear there. It can then be saved as
"rexx:CheckLib.rexx".

Users of MultiView and the V39 AmigaGuide library don't have block and
copy capability. You can save the program, though, by opening the
Viewport file in a text editor. Search for "@Node ARXTEXAMPLE".
Highlight everything from the opening comment marker to the line above
"@REM Include only the lines above this one."

@EndNode

@Node ARXTEXAMPLE "Viewport ARexx tutorial -- CheckLib.rexx"
@NEXT ARXTUTORIAL
/* $VER CheckLib.rexx 1.0 (100793)
**
** Adds a library to the Library list, and calls one of its functions
** to load the library.
**
** Syntax is the same as that used by ADDLIB() except that the Priority,
** Offset, and Version numbers may all be omitted.
**
*/

parse arg LibName, Priority, Offset, Version

if LibName = '' then return 0    /* Must include a library name */

signal on syntax

if ~show('L', LibName) then do  /* Is the library already on the list? */
      /* Set defaults for ADDLIB() */
   if Priority = '' then Priority = 0
   if Offset = '' then Offset = -30
   if Version = '' then Version = 0
      /* The return from the function doesn't matter, so use CALL      */
   call addlib(LibName, Priority, Offset, Version)
end

   /* This call to a non-existent (I hope) function will force all     **
   ** libraries to be loaded. It will generate a syntax error (#15)    **
   ** but that will be trapped by the SIGNAL instruction               */
call FooBarian()

   /* Unlikely we'd make it this far, but maybe someone will use       **
   ** 'FooBarian' as a function name.                                  */
return 1

syntax:

      /* This subroutine will be called on any syntax error. The call  **
      ** to FooBarian() above is almost guaranteed to generate an      **
      ** error. We're interested in the type of error. #14 means that  **
      ** the library we tried to load isn't available. #15 is OK. It   **
      ** means "Function not found" and we expect that.                */

   if rc = 14 then do
      call remlib(LibName)
      return 0
   else
      return 1    /* Function not found, but library was loaded        */

@REM Include only the lines above this one.
@EndNode

@Node ARXTNAME "ViewPort ARexx Tutorial -- ADDLIB() <library name> argument"
@PREV ARXTUTORIAL
The <library name> argument is case sensitive: "REXXSupport.Library" is
not the same thing as "rexxsupport.library". Library names are usually
written in lowercase, but there are some exceptions. Be careful to use
the correct case; otherwise the desired functions will not be made
available to ARexx. Be careful also to enclose the library name in
quotation marks. ARexx converts symbols to uppercase if they are not
quoted. Such a shift would cause the wrong name to be sent to the
function.

Unless an explicit path is specified in the argument string, ARexx will
look for the library when needed in the system libs: directory.

@EndNode
@Node ARXTPRI "ViewPort ARexx Tutorial -- ADDLIB() <priority> argument"

<priority> is an integer between -100 and 100. It may be chosen by the
user and controls the order in which ARexx will search for a
function-name match within the libraries.

A library with a higher priority number will be searched before other
libraries.

When a function is called and several entries are included on the
Library List, ARexx passes the function name to each of the libraries in
turn. A library will send a code back to ARexx indicating if a match was
made. This takes some time, so it may be desirable to assure that a
frequently-used library is searched early.

If several libraries are added to the list with the same priority, ARexx
will search them in the order they were added.

@EndNode
@Node ARXTOFF "ViewPort ARexx Tutorial -- ADDLIB() <offset> argument"

The <offset> number for a library must be specified by the library's
developer. For rexxsupport.library and most of the other packages
released so far, the number is -30.
@EndNode
@Node ARXTVER "ViewPort ARexx Tutorial -- ADDLIB() <version> argument"
@NEXT ARXTUTORIAL

Many function libraries change over time, adding and changing functions
available in the package. By specifying a <version> number when ADDLIB()
is called, the programmer can limit the library to a version number
equal to or higher than the number specified here.

Check each library's documentation for valid version numbers.

If 0 is specified, any available version of the library will be loaded.

@EndNode

@Node ARXTHOST "ViewPort ARexx Tutorial -- Function hosts"
@NEXT ARXTUTORIAL 80
@PREV ARXTUTORIAL 80

It's actually possible to have a valid name on the library list even
when a library with a matching name does not exist. Although the method
is rarely used, functions can also be added to the system through a
program that sets itself up as an ARexx function host. If that happens,
the name on the library list will match one of the names on the list of
message ports, which can be viewed with this shell command:

   rx "say show('P',,'0a'x)

One function host available on many online libraries is QuickSort. This
is a program that adds just one function to ARexx, but it's very useful
-- a fast sorting routine. The host is added to the library list with
the name QuickSortPort.

@EndNode

